{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"47e16fb7-a647-45b0-9781-a29b0d8e5d97","content":"Here's my analysis of the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Deep Import Chain (level1 → level2 → level3)\n\nThe project imports `level1.props`, which imports `level2.props`, which imports `level3.props`. Each nested import requires MSBuild to locate, open, parse, and evaluate an additional file during the **evaluation phase**. Deep chains increase disk I/O and XML parsing overhead linearly, and make property/item resolution order harder to reason about.\n\n## 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern\n\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n\nThe `**\\*.*` glob recursively scans the entire directory tree. It only excludes `bin` and `obj`, so it will still enumerate directories like `.git`, `node_modules`, `packages`, or any other large unrelated subtrees. Glob expansion happens during evaluation, so a large working tree dramatically slows it down. **Fix:** restrict to specific folders/extensions or add entries to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n## 3. Property Function Performing File I/O During Evaluation\n\n```xml\n<BuildNotes Condition=\"Exists('build-notes.txt')\">$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n\nThis calls `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` at evaluation time. Property functions execute during the evaluation phase—not the build execution phase—so every project load (IDE open, restore, design-time build) pays this cost. File I/O in evaluation is especially harmful because evaluation should be fast and side-effect-free.\n\n## Evaluation vs. Execution Phase\n\nMSBuild has two distinct phases:\n- **Evaluation** – parses XML, expands properties/items/imports, resolves globs. Runs on every IDE interaction and `dotnet restore`.\n- **Execution** – runs targets/tasks (Compile, Copy, etc.) only during actual builds.\n\nAll three issues above occur during evaluation, meaning they slow down *every* interaction with the project, not just builds. Keep evaluation lightweight by minimizing imports, tightening globs, and deferring I/O to targets.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f1703bb-c140-4769-a117-4f56b0eb3788","outputTokens":520,"requestId":"EC13:1745CF:84F70D:A4FCF7:6A013221"},"id":"c4340d08-4240-4699-bb02-9392cc401856","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:34:38.272Z","parentId":"ca3c7e21-57ca-4712-8b0b-ac20d3dd4fc8"}
